<author><name><![CDATA[Jarhmander]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-10-22T19:38:42-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-10-22T19:38:42-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8225&amp;p=85477#p85477</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8225&amp;p=85477#p85477"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Digital IC's based analog amplifiers]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8225&amp;p=85477#p85477"><![CDATA[
Negative feedback can lead to instability, if there's too much gain when phase lags by 180˚ (negative feedback becomes positive feedback at this point, and you know it's instable). So either reduce the amount of feedback, or stick in a small cap either at the input or output to further reduce gain at high-frequencies. But the fact that the output is buffered can indeed not help.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=336">Jarhmander</a> — Sat Oct 22, 2011 7:38 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
